	(35,1,'2015-03-22 22:37:11','2015-03-22 22:37:11','','Home Depot','','trash','open','open','','home-depot-2','','','2015-04-25 14:44:00','2015-04-25 14:44:00','',0,'http://localhost:8888/seniorsoutdoors/?tribe_venue=home-depot-2',0,'tribe_venue','',0),
	(37,1,'2015-03-22 22:43:56','2015-03-22 22:43:56','We will camp in a primitive area on the north end of the lake accessed by a 15 mile 4WD road. Activities will include hiking and exploring the area, paddling, fishing. It may also be warm enough for swimming. We usually have fresh fish for dinner. Length of trip : 3 or 4 days.\r\n\r\nNote: Departure point, time and actual dates will be set by participants','Lake Powell car camping trip','','publish','open','closed','','lake-powell-car-camping-trip-2','','','2015-05-09 17:20:40','2015-05-09 17:20:40','',0,'http://localhost:8888/seniorsoutdoors/?post_type=tribe_events&#038;p=37',0,'tribe_events','',0),
	(38,1,'2015-03-22 22:52:25','2015-03-22 22:52:25','Located within the city limits on the north end of town, this trail has a consistent uphill from the trailhead along the outside edge of the mountain to the promontory at the top. Trail is rocky. Poles may be helpful. Great views of Durango &amp; the Animas Valley along the way and at the top.   The trip will either return on the same trail or by an interior trail with approximately the same return distance.','WW hike:  Animas City Mountain','','publish','open','closed','','ww-hike-animas-city-mountain','','','2015-05-09 17:20:33','2015-05-09 17:20:33','',0,'http://localhost:8888/seniorsoutdoors/?post_type=tribe_events&#038;p=38',0,'tribe_events','',0),
	(39,1,'2015-03-22 23:12:18','2015-03-22 23:12:18','We will start at the trailhead located at the Animas High School parking lot. The trail takes us to the base of the left larger butte, where you will have the option to climb or wait until we descend the butte. We will continue along the trail that goes around the Twin Buttes and then meet up with the starting trail to return to the trailhead.','Hike Twin Buttes Trail','','publish','open','closed','','hike-twin-buttes-trail-and-climb-left-larger-butte','','','2015-05-09 17:20:27','2015-05-09 17:20:27','',0,'http://localhost:8888/seniorsoutdoors/?post_type=tribe_events&#038;p=39',0,'tribe_events','',0),
	(40,1,'2015-03-23 01:27:25','2015-03-23 01:27:25','<h3 class=\"purple-dark\">The Antarctic: Excursion to the South Pole</h3>\r\nAnne Dal Vera and 3 other women were the first women to ski to the South Pole from the edge of the continent. Head over to the May General Meeting and learn about their adventures on the ice and snow of Antarctica.','SO! General Meeting','','publish','open','open','','so-general-meeting','','','2015-05-09 20:07:43','2015-05-09 20:07:43','',0,'http://localhost:8888/seniorsoutdoors/?post_type=tribe_events&#038;p=40',0,'tribe_events','',0),
	(41,1,'2015-03-23 01:29:38','2015-03-23 01:29:38','We will hike up Red Creek <span class=\"GramE\">Trail,</span> follow Missionary Ridge Trail west to its intersection with First Fork, which returns to the trailhead. Nice views from Missionary Ridge and a good early-season, low elevation, conditioning hike.','Red Creek–First Fork Loop','','publish','open','closed','','red-creek-first-fork-loop','','','2015-05-09 17:19:46','2015-05-09 17:19:46','',0,'http://localhost:8888/seniorsoutdoors/?post_type=tribe_events&#038;p=41',0,'tribe_events','',0),
	(42,1,'2015-03-23 01:32:14','2015-03-23 01:32:14','On this hike, from the parking lot we will follow the Twin Buttes trail to the upper junction with the BC&amp;F trail. Then down the BC&amp;F trail to it’s lower junction with the Twin Buttes Trail and back to the parking lot. Dogs are OK, but must be on leash as this entire area is in the Durango city limits. Early turn backs are not permitted unless you have a map and a working knowledge of the new trail system.','WW hike:  Twin Buttes I','','publish','open','closed','','ww-hike-twin-buttes-i','','','2015-05-09 17:19:27','2015-05-09 17:19:27','',0,'http://localhost:8888/seniorsoutdoors/?post_type=tribe_events&#038;p=42',0,'tribe_events','',0),
	(43,1,'2015-03-24 17:47:24','2015-03-24 17:47:24','We will hike down from the Purg Flats Trail Head across from DMR to the Animas River Footbridge and have lunch. Dogs OK if their humans are under control.','Purgatory Flats to the Animas River','','publish','open','closed','','purgatory-flats-to-the-animas-river','','','2015-05-09 17:19:11','2015-05-09 17:19:11','',0,'http://localhost:8888/seniorsoutdoors/?post_type=tribe_events&#038;p=43',0,'tribe_events','',0),
	(44,1,'2015-03-24 17:49:35','2015-03-24 17:49:35','This hike will be an interpretive hike led by MK Thompson of the SJMA into an area of the Mancos River. We estimate about 3 hours of hiking time and 45 min each way drive time so bring lunch or substantial snack. From FR 561, this loop begins with a descent through lush vegetation down the Box Canyon trail.  The descent is steep but has nice steps and water bars for assistance.  After a bit more than half a mile, we will connect with the Transfer trail.  This trail rolls up and down as we head upstream along the West Mancos River.  There are many opportunities for stops by the stream as well as evidence of animals including squirrel <span class=\"SpellE\">middens</span> and bear claw marks.  About 2 miles in, we will begin our climb back up to the rim.  Notice the transition from lush berry bushes, blue spruce, and Douglass fir to sun loving scrub oak, ponderosa pines, and aspens.  Once we top out the climb at around mile 2.7, we will join the Rim Trail.  This trail rolls gently and mostly downhill.  Since we are up on the rim now, keep your eyes peeled for soaring birds such as red tailed hawks.  There are also lovely rock formations.','WW Mancos: Box Canyon','','publish','open','closed','','ww-mancosbox-canyontransferrim-trails-loop-hike','','','2015-05-09 17:18:48','2015-05-09 17:18:48','',0,'http://localhost:8888/seniorsoutdoors/?post_type=tribe_events&#038;p=44',0,'tribe_events','',0),
	(45,1,'2015-03-24 17:52:35','2015-03-24 17:52:35','We’ll hike the switchbacks up Goulding Creek (most of the elevation gain), follow the ridge south on the Pinkerton Flagstaff Trail, and descend on the Jones Creek Trail to Hermosa Creek.','Goulding Creek Trail to Jones Creek','','publish','open','closed','','goulding-creek-trail-to-jones-creek-a-through-hike','','','2015-05-09 17:18:34','2015-05-09 17:18:34','',0,'http://localhost:8888/seniorsoutdoors/?post_type=tribe_events&#038;p=45',0,'tribe_events','',0),
	(46,1,'2015-03-24 17:56:10','2015-03-24 17:56:10','Larry will lead us on a series of hikes to find some of northern New Mexico’s many arches. The group will drive on oil &amp; gas roads to several locations and then take short hikes to find arches.','New Mexico Arch Hunting','','publish','open','closed','','new-mexico-arch-hunting-with-larry-beck','','','2015-05-09 17:18:18','2015-05-09 17:18:18','',0,'http://localhost:8888/seniorsoutdoors/?post_type=tribe_events&#038;p=46',0,'tribe_events','',0),
	(47,1,'2015-03-24 17:58:54','2015-03-24 17:58:54','We will hike at a casual pace to the first bridge at the most. Some may want to stop at a nice creek view about 2/3 of the way to the first bridge (Jim and Rhonda\'s lunch spot). Early turn backs with partner ok.','WW hike:  Vallecito Creek Trail','','publish','open','closed','','ww-hike-vallecito-creek-trail','','','2015-05-09 19:52:34','2015-05-09 19:52:34','',0,'http://localhost:8888/seniorsoutdoors/?post_type=tribe_events&#038;p=47',0,'tribe_events','',0),
